When exposed at different temperatures from 450 to 600°C for 100h, both the 35V and the 25V alloys experienced different degrees of oxidation on their surfaces, as shown in Fig. 3

[15]. When exposed at a temperature lower than 550°C, both the 35V and the 25V alloys exhibited little mass gain, indicating that their mechanical properties may not be affected significantly by oxidation. However, oxidation rates increased quickly as temperature increased above 550°C. At 600°C, a thick oxide was observed spalling off the surface after tensile testing. That oxide layer was responsible for a severe loss of the ductility. Fractograph analysis revealed that brittle intergranular failure tended to occur in the 35V and the 25V alloys (Fig. 4
).

α Phases precipitated in the 25V alloy with low V content well distributed in grains and/or on grain boundaries (Fig. 8
), and at the mean time lots of dislocations were easily discovered around the α phases (Fig. 9
), which retarded the movement of the dislocations. However, most of α phases distributed in grains and grain boundaries, causing stress concentration on grain boundaries and the matrices understanding bigger stress. The α precipitates distributed heterogeneously within grains decreased the deformation resistance of the inter-grains, which leads to the sliding of grain boundaries and increase of residual strain, resulting in decrease in creep resistance. The creep resistance of the 35V alloy was better than that of the 25V alloy. This was because of most of α precipitates in the 35V alloy distributing as continuous α layer or plate-like α on grain boundaries (Fig. 8a and b). This grain boundary α was good to strength, however, was bad to plasticity, reducing the sliding of grain boundary and sliding strength, which increased the creep resistance.
